cs.PL, cs.LO, cs.SE, cs.FL, cs.CL 

This paper is likely to belong to the Programming Languages (cs.PL) category as it introduces a new approach to turning a programming language into a proof assistant. It also involves the use of combinators and uninterpreted symbols, which are common concepts in the PL community. 

It could also belong to the Logic in Computer Science (cs.LO) category as it involves encoding functions and lambdas using uninterpreted symbols in a logic. 

Software Engineering (cs.SE) is another possible category as the paper discusses a tool, Liquid Haskell, that implements the approach and can be used for verification. 

Formal Languages and Automata Theory (cs.FL) is a possible category as the paper involves encoding functions and lambdas in a logic, which is a fundamental concept in formal language theory. 

Finally, the paper could also belong to the Computation and Language (cs.CL) category as it involves the use of a programming language to verify properties of higher order, recursive functions and type class laws.
